inflammation","Thrombotic occlusion"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EHyperplastic arteriolosclerosis is a vascular change primarily affecting small arterioles, commonly seen in patients with severe or malignant hypertension. It occurs due to the body\u0027s response to elevated blood pressure, causing vascular remodeling.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EConcentric smooth muscle proliferation\u003C/strong\u003E is the classic microscopic finding in hyperplastic arteriolosclerosis. This appears as an \u0022onion-skin\u0022 layering of smooth muscle cells in the vessel wall, significantly narrowing the lumen. This finding is characteristic in patients with poorly controlled, longstanding hypertension as described in the case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHomogeneous eosinophilic thickening\u003C/strong\u003E is characteristic of hyaline arteriolosclerosis, which is seen in milder forms of hypertension and diabetes mellitus, representing plasma protein leakage and accumulation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFibrinoid necrosis\u003C/strong\u003E is typically seen in malignant hypertension or vasculitis, representing acute vascular injury rather than chronic changes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGranulomatous inflammation\u003C/strong\u003E would suggest vasculitis such as granulomatosis with polyangiitis, which is a different pathological process entirely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThrombotic occlusion\u003C/strong\u003E would be seen in conditions such as thrombotic microangiopathy or antiphospholipid syndrome, rather than the chronic vascular changes of hyperplastic arteriolosclerosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHyperplastic arteriolosclerosis represents a more severe form of hypertensive vascular damage than hyaline arteriolosclerosis. It can lead to significant reduction in organ perfusion over time, particularly affecting the kidneys, contributing to declining renal function as mentioned in the case.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Hyperplastic arteriolosclerosis is characterised by concentric smooth muscle proliferation in arteriolar walls","Hyperplastic arteriolosclerosis is commonly associated with severe or malignant hypertension","Hyperplastic arteriolosclerosis primarily affects small arterioles and can lead to significant luminal narrowing"],"references":["Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Philadelphia: Elsevier; 2020. Chapter 11; pages 493-494"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"76338"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20537"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"76338","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/76338"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-20T12:15:23+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-20T12:16:53+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13416"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"92985"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4914","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4914"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Blood vessels","synonyms":[],"